8 ///
9 /// \file
10 /// This file describes how to lower LLVM code to machine code. This has two
11 /// main components:
12 ///
13 /// 1. Which ValueTypes are natively supported by the target.
14 /// 2. Which operations are supported for supported ValueTypes.
15 /// 3. Cost thresholds for alternative implementations of certain operations.
16 ///
17 /// In addition it has a few other components, like information about FP
18 /// immediates.
19 ///
20 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//
21

98 enum Preference {
99  None, // No preference
100  Source, // Follow source order.
101  RegPressure, // Scheduling for lowest register pressure.
102  Hybrid, // Scheduling for both latency and register pressure.
103  ILP, // Scheduling for ILP in low register pressure mode.
104  VLIW, // Scheduling for VLIW targets.
105  Fast, // Fast suboptimal list scheduling
106  Linearize // Linearize DAG, no scheduling
107 };
108 
109 } // end namespace Sched

111 // MemOp models a memory operation, either memset or memcpy/memmove.
112 struct MemOp {
113 private:
114  // Shared
115  uint64_t Size;
116  bool DstAlignCanChange; // true if destination alignment can satisfy any
117  // constraint.
118  Align DstAlign; // Specified alignment of the memory operation.
119 
120  bool AllowOverlap;
121  // memset only
122  bool IsMemset; // If setthis memory operation is a memset.
123  bool ZeroMemset; // If set clears out memory with zeros.
124  // memcpy only
125  bool MemcpyStrSrc; // Indicates whether the memcpy source is an in-register
126  // constant so it does not need to be loaded.
127  Align SrcAlign; // Inferred alignment of the source or default value if the
128  // memory operation does not need to load the value.
129 public:
130  static MemOp Copy(uint64_t Size, bool DstAlignCanChange, Align DstAlign,
131  Align SrcAlign, bool IsVolatile,
132  bool MemcpyStrSrc = false) {
133  MemOp Op;
134  Op.Size = Size;
135  Op.DstAlignCanChange = DstAlignCanChange;
136  Op.DstAlign = DstAlign;
137  Op.AllowOverlap = !IsVolatile;
138  Op.IsMemset = false;
139  Op.ZeroMemset = false;
140  Op.MemcpyStrSrc = MemcpyStrSrc;
141  Op.SrcAlign = SrcAlign;
142  return Op;
143  }
144 
145  static MemOp Set(uint64_t Size, bool DstAlignCanChange, Align DstAlign,
146  bool IsZeroMemset, bool IsVolatile) {
147  MemOp Op;
148  Op.Size = Size;
149  Op.DstAlignCanChange = DstAlignCanChange;
150  Op.DstAlign = DstAlign;
151  Op.AllowOverlap = !IsVolatile;
152  Op.IsMemset = true;
153  Op.ZeroMemset = IsZeroMemset;
154  Op.MemcpyStrSrc = false;
155  return Op;
156  }
157 
158  uint64_t size() const { return Size; }
159  Align getDstAlign() const {
160  assert(!DstAlignCanChange);
161  return DstAlign;
162  }
163  bool isFixedDstAlign() const { return !DstAlignCanChange; }
164  bool allowOverlap() const { return AllowOverlap; }
165  bool isMemset() const { return IsMemset; }
166  bool isMemcpy() const { return !IsMemset; }
167  bool isMemcpyWithFixedDstAlign() const {
168  return isMemcpy() && !DstAlignCanChange;
169  }
170  bool isZeroMemset() const { return isMemset() && ZeroMemset; }
171  bool isMemcpyStrSrc() const {
172  assert(isMemcpy() && "Must be a memcpy");
173  return MemcpyStrSrc;
174  }
175  Align getSrcAlign() const {
176  assert(isMemcpy() && "Must be a memcpy");
177  return SrcAlign;
178  }
179  bool isSrcAligned(Align AlignCheck) const {
180  return isMemset() || llvm::isAligned(AlignCheck, SrcAlign.value());
181  }
182  bool isDstAligned(Align AlignCheck) const {
183  return DstAlignCanChange || llvm::isAligned(AlignCheck, DstAlign.value());
184  }
185  bool isAligned(Align AlignCheck) const {
186  return isSrcAligned(AlignCheck) && isDstAligned(AlignCheck);
187  }
188 };
189 
190 /// This base class for TargetLowering contains the SelectionDAG-independent
191 /// parts that can be used from the rest of CodeGen.
192 class TargetLoweringBase {
193 public:
194  /// This enum indicates whether operations are valid for a target, and if not,
195  /// what action should be used to make them valid.
196  enum LegalizeAction : uint8_t {
197  Legal, // The target natively supports this operation.
198  Promote, // This operation should be executed in a larger type.
199  Expand, // Try to expand this to other ops, otherwise use a libcall.
200  LibCall, // Don't try to expand this to other ops, always use a libcall.
201  Custom // Use the LowerOperation hook to implement custom lowering.
202  };
203 
204  /// This enum indicates whether a types are legal for a target, and if not,
205  /// what action should be used to make them valid.
206  enum LegalizeTypeAction : uint8_t {
207  TypeLegal, // The target natively supports this type.
208  TypePromoteInteger, // Replace this integer with a larger one.
209  TypeExpandInteger, // Split this integer into two of half the size.
210  TypeSoftenFloat, // Convert this float to a same size integer type.
211  TypeExpandFloat, // Split this float into two of half the size.
212  TypeScalarizeVector, // Replace this one-element vector with its element.
213  TypeSplitVector, // Split this vector into two of half the size.
214  TypeWidenVector, // This vector should be widened into a larger vector.
215  TypePromoteFloat, // Replace this float with a larger one.
216  TypeSoftPromoteHalf, // Soften half to i16 and use float to do arithmetic.
217  TypeScalarizeScalableVector, // This action is explicitly left unimplemented.
218  // While it is theoretically possible to
219  // legalize operations on scalable types with a
220  // loop that handles the vscale * #lanes of the
221  // vector, this is non-trivial at SelectionDAG
222  // level and these types are better to be
223  // widened or promoted.
224  };
225 
226  /// LegalizeKind holds the legalization kind that needs to happen to EVT
227  /// in order to type-legalize it.
228  using LegalizeKind = std::pair<LegalizeTypeAction, EVT>;
229 
230  /// Enum that describes how the target represents true/false values.
231  enum BooleanContent {
232  UndefinedBooleanContent, // Only bit 0 counts, the rest can hold garbage.
233  ZeroOrOneBooleanContent, // All bits zero except for bit 0.
234  ZeroOrNegativeOneBooleanContent // All bits equal to bit 0.
235  };
236 
237  /// Enum that describes what type of support for selects the target has.
238  enum SelectSupportKind {
239  ScalarValSelect, // The target supports scalar selects (ex: cmov).
240  ScalarCondVectorVal, // The target supports selects with a scalar condition
241  // and vector values (ex: cmov).
242  VectorMaskSelect // The target supports vector selects with a vector
243  // mask (ex: x86 blends).
244  };
245 
246  /// Enum that specifies what an atomic load/AtomicRMWInst is expanded
247  /// to, if at all. Exists because different targets have different levels of
248  /// support for these atomic instructions, and also have different options
249  /// w.r.t. what they should expand to.
250  enum class AtomicExpansionKind {
251  None, // Don't expand the instruction.
252  CastToInteger, // Cast the atomic instruction to another type, e.g. from
253  // floating-point to integer type.
254  LLSC, // Expand the instruction into loadlinked/storeconditional; used
255  // by ARM/AArch64.
256  LLOnly, // Expand the (load) instruction into just a load-linked, which has
257  // greater atomic guarantees than a normal load.
258  CmpXChg, // Expand the instruction into cmpxchg; used by at least X86.
259  MaskedIntrinsic, // Use a target-specific intrinsic for the LL/SC loop.
260  BitTestIntrinsic, // Use a target-specific intrinsic for special bit
261  // operations; used by X86.
262  CmpArithIntrinsic,// Use a target-specific intrinsic for special compare
263  // operations; used by X86.
264  Expand, // Generic expansion in terms of other atomic operations.
265 
266  // Rewrite to a non-atomic form for use in a known non-preemptible
267  // environment.
268  NotAtomic
269  };
270 
271  /// Enum that specifies when a multiplication should be expanded.
272  enum class MulExpansionKind {
273  Always, // Always expand the instruction.
274  OnlyLegalOrCustom, // Only expand when the resulting instructions are legal
275  // or custom.
276  };
277 
278  /// Enum that specifies when a float negation is beneficial.
279  enum class NegatibleCost {
280  Cheaper = 0, // Negated expression is cheaper.
281  Neutral = 1, // Negated expression has the same cost.
282  Expensive = 2 // Negated expression is more expensive.
283  };
284 
285  /// Enum of different potentially desirable ways to fold (and/or (setcc ...),
286  /// (setcc ...)).
287  enum class AndOrSETCCFoldKind {
288  None,
289  AddAnd,
290  ABS,
291  };

325  virtual void markLibCallAttributes(MachineFunction *MF, unsigned CC,

327 
328  static ISD::NodeType getExtendForContent(BooleanContent Content) {
329  switch (Content) {
330  case UndefinedBooleanContent:
331  // Extend by adding rubbish bits.
332  return ISD::ANY_EXTEND;
333  case ZeroOrOneBooleanContent:
334  // Extend by adding zero bits.
335  return ISD::ZERO_EXTEND;
336  case ZeroOrNegativeOneBooleanContent:
337  // Extend by copying the sign bit.
338  return ISD::SIGN_EXTEND;
339  }
340  llvm_unreachable("Invalid content kind");
341  }

362  /// Return the pointer type for the given address space, defaults to
363  /// the pointer type from the data layout.
364  /// FIXME: The default needs to be removed once all the code is updated.
365  virtual MVT getPointerTy(const DataLayout &DL, uint32_t AS = 0) const {
366  return MVT::getIntegerVT(DL.getPointerSizeInBits(AS));
367  }
368 
369  /// Return the in-memory pointer type for the given address space, defaults to
370  /// the pointer type from the data layout. FIXME: The default needs to be
371  /// removed once all the code is updated.
372  virtual MVT getPointerMemTy(const DataLayout &DL, uint32_t AS = 0) const {
373  return MVT::getIntegerVT(DL.getPointerSizeInBits(AS));
374  }
375 
376  /// Return the type for frame index, which is determined by
377  /// the alloca address space specified through the data layout.
378  MVT getFrameIndexTy(const DataLayout &DL) const {
379  return getPointerTy(DL, DL.getAllocaAddrSpace());
380  }
381 
382  /// Return the type for code pointers, which is determined by the program
383  /// address space specified through the data layout.
384  MVT getProgramPointerTy(const DataLayout &DL) const {
385  return getPointerTy(DL, DL.getProgramAddressSpace());
386  }

388  /// Return the type for operands of fence.
389  /// TODO: Let fence operands be of i32 type and remove this.

391  return getPointerTy(DL);
392  }

394  /// Return the type to use for a scalar shift opcode, given the shifted amount
395  /// type. Targets should return a legal type if the input type is legal.
396  /// Targets can return a type that is too small if the input type is illegal.
397  virtual MVT getScalarShiftAmountTy(const DataLayout &, EVT) const;
398 
399  /// Returns the type for the shift amount of a shift opcode. For vectors,
400  /// returns the input type. For scalars, behavior depends on \p LegalTypes. If
401  /// \p LegalTypes is true, calls getScalarShiftAmountTy, otherwise uses
402  /// pointer type. If getScalarShiftAmountTy or pointer type cannot represent
403  /// all possible shift amounts, returns MVT::i32. In general, \p LegalTypes
404  /// should be set to true for calls during type legalization and after type
405  /// legalization has been completed.
406  EVT getShiftAmountTy(EVT LHSTy, const DataLayout &DL,
407  bool LegalTypes = true) const;
408 
409  /// Return the preferred type to use for a shift opcode, given the shifted
410  /// amount type is \p ShiftValueTy.
411  LLVM_READONLY
412  virtual LLT getPreferredShiftAmountTy(LLT ShiftValueTy) const {
413  return ShiftValueTy;
414  }

477  /// Return the preferred vector type legalization action.
478  virtual TargetLoweringBase::LegalizeTypeAction
479  getPreferredVectorAction(MVT VT) const {
480  // The default action for one element vectors is to scalarize
481  if (VT.getVectorElementCount().isScalar())
482  return TypeScalarizeVector;
483  // The default action for an odd-width vector is to widen.
484  if (!VT.isPow2VectorType())
485  return TypeWidenVector;
486  // The default action for other vectors is to promote
487  return TypePromoteInteger;
488  }
489 
490  // Return true if the half type should be passed around as i16, but promoted
491  // to float around arithmetic. The default behavior is to pass around as
492  // float and convert around loads/stores/bitcasts and other places where
493  // the size matters.
494  virtual bool softPromoteHalfType() const { return false; }
495 
496  // There are two general methods for expanding a BUILD_VECTOR node:
497  // 1. Use SCALAR_TO_VECTOR on the defined scalar values and then shuffle
498  // them together.
499  // 2. Build the vector on the stack and then load it.
500  // If this function returns true, then method (1) will be used, subject to
501  // the constraint that all of the necessary shuffles are legal (as determined
502  // by isShuffleMaskLegal). If this function returns false, then method (2) is
503  // always used. The vector type, and the number of defined values, are
504  // provided.
505  virtual bool
506  shouldExpandBuildVectorWithShuffles(EVT /* VT */,
507  unsigned DefinedValues) const {
508  return DefinedValues < 3;
509  }
510 
511  /// Return true if integer divide is usually cheaper than a sequence of
512  /// several shifts, adds, and multiplies for this target.
513  /// The definition of "cheaper" may depend on whether we're optimizing
514  /// for speed or for size.
515  virtual bool isIntDivCheap(EVT VT, AttributeList Attr) const { return false; }
516 
517  /// Return true if the target can handle a standalone remainder operation.
518  virtual bool hasStandaloneRem(EVT VT) const {
519  return true;
520  }
521 
522  /// Return true if SQRT(X) shouldn't be replaced with X*RSQRT(X).
523  virtual bool isFsqrtCheap(SDValue X, SelectionDAG &DAG) const {
524  // Default behavior is to replace SQRT(X) with X*RSQRT(X).
525  return false;
526  }

528  /// Reciprocal estimate status values used by the functions below.

585  /// Return true if the following transform is beneficial:
586  /// fold (conv (load x)) -> (load (conv*)x)
587  /// On architectures that don't natively support some vector loads
588  /// efficiently, casting the load to a smaller vector of larger types and
589  /// loading is more efficient, however, this can be undone by optimizations in
590  /// dag combiner.
591  virtual bool isLoadBitCastBeneficial(EVT LoadVT, EVT BitcastVT,
592  const SelectionDAG &DAG,
593  const MachineMemOperand &MMO) const;
594 
595  /// Return true if the following transform is beneficial:
596  /// (store (y (conv x)), y*)) -> (store x, (x*))
597  virtual bool isStoreBitCastBeneficial(EVT StoreVT, EVT BitcastVT,
598  const SelectionDAG &DAG,
599  const MachineMemOperand &MMO) const {
600  // Default to the same logic as loads.
601  return isLoadBitCastBeneficial(StoreVT, BitcastVT, DAG, MMO);
602  }

604  /// Return true if it is expected to be cheaper to do a store of a non-zero
605  /// vector constant with the given size and type for the address space than to
606  /// store the individual scalar element constants.
607  virtual bool storeOfVectorConstantIsCheap(EVT MemVT,
608  unsigned NumElem,
609  unsigned AddrSpace) const {
610  return false;
611  }

613  /// Allow store merging for the specified type after legalization in addition
614  /// to before legalization. This may transform stores that do not exist
615  /// earlier (for example, stores created from intrinsics).
616  virtual bool mergeStoresAfterLegalization(EVT MemVT) const {

661  /// Return if the target supports combining a

675  /// Use bitwise logic to make pairs of compares more efficient. For example:

684  /// Return the preferred operand type if the target has a quick way to compare
685  /// integer values of the given size. Assume that any legal integer type can
686  /// be compared efficiently. Targets may override this to allow illegal wide
687  /// types to return a vector type if there is support to compare that type.
688  virtual MVT hasFastEqualityCompare(unsigned NumBits) const {
689  MVT VT = MVT::getIntegerVT(NumBits);
690  return isTypeLegal(VT) ? VT : MVT::INVALID_SIMPLE_VALUE_TYPE;
691  }

693  /// Return true if the target should transform:
694  /// (X & Y) == Y ---> (~X & Y) == 0
695  /// (X & Y) != Y ---> (~X & Y) != 0
696  ///
697  /// This may be profitable if the target has a bitwise and-not operation that
698  /// sets comparison flags. A target may want to limit the transformation based
699  /// on the type of Y or if Y is a constant.
700  ///
701  /// Note that the transform will not occur if Y is known to be a power-of-2
702  /// because a mask and compare of a single bit can be handled by inverting the
703  /// predicate, for example:
704  /// (X & 8) == 8 ---> (X & 8) != 0
705  virtual bool hasAndNotCompare(SDValue Y) const {
706  return false;
707  }
708 
709  /// Return true if the target has a bitwise and-not operation:
710  /// X = ~A & B
711  /// This can be used to simplify select or other instructions.
712  virtual bool hasAndNot(SDValue X) const {
713  // If the target has the more complex version of this operation, assume that
714  // it has this operation too.
715  return hasAndNotCompare(X);
716  }
717 
718  /// Return true if the target has a bit-test instruction:
719  /// (X & (1 << Y)) ==/!= 0
720  /// This knowledge can be used to prevent breaking the pattern,
721  /// or creating it if it could be recognized.
722  virtual bool hasBitTest(SDValue X, SDValue Y) const { return false; }
723 
724  /// There are two ways to clear extreme bits (either low or high):
725  /// Mask: x & (-1 << y) (the instcombine canonical form)
726  /// Shifts: x >> y << y
727  /// Return true if the variant with 2 variable shifts is preferred.
728  /// Return false if there is no preference.
729  virtual bool shouldFoldMaskToVariableShiftPair(SDValue X) const {
730  // By default, let's assume that no one prefers shifts.
731  return false;
732  }
733 
734  /// Return true if it is profitable to fold a pair of shifts into a mask.
735  /// This is usually true on most targets. But some targets, like Thumb1,
736  /// have immediate shift instructions, but no immediate "and" instruction;
737  /// this makes the fold unprofitable.
738  virtual bool shouldFoldConstantShiftPairToMask(const SDNode *N,
739  CombineLevel Level) const {
740  return true;
741  }
742 
743  /// Should we tranform the IR-optimal check for whether given truncation
744  /// down into KeptBits would be truncating or not:
745  /// (add %x, (1 << (KeptBits-1))) srccond (1 << KeptBits)
746  /// Into it's more traditional form:
747  /// ((%x << C) a>> C) dstcond %x
748  /// Return true if we should transform.
749  /// Return false if there is no preference.
750  virtual bool shouldTransformSignedTruncationCheck(EVT XVT,
751  unsigned KeptBits) const {
752  // By default, let's assume that no one prefers shifts.
753  return false;
754  }
755 
756  /// Given the pattern
757  /// (X & (C l>>/<< Y)) ==/!= 0
758  /// return true if it should be transformed into:
759  /// ((X <</l>> Y) & C) ==/!= 0
760  /// WARNING: if 'X' is a constant, the fold may deadlock!
761  /// FIXME: we could avoid passing XC, but we can't use isConstOrConstSplat()
762  /// here because it can end up being not linked in.
763  virtual bool shouldProduceAndByConstByHoistingConstFromShiftsLHSOfAnd(
764  SDValue X, ConstantSDNode *XC, ConstantSDNode *CC, SDValue Y,
765  unsigned OldShiftOpcode, unsigned NewShiftOpcode,
766  SelectionDAG &DAG) const {
767  if (hasBitTest(X, Y)) {
768  // One interesting pattern that we'd want to form is 'bit test':
769  // ((1 << Y) & C) ==/!= 0
770  // But we also need to be careful not to try to reverse that fold.
771 
772  // Is this '1 << Y' ?
773  if (OldShiftOpcode == ISD::SHL && CC->isOne())
774  return false; // Keep the 'bit test' pattern.
775 
776  // Will it be '1 << Y' after the transform ?
777  if (XC && NewShiftOpcode == ISD::SHL && XC->isOne())
778  return true; // Do form the 'bit test' pattern.
779  }
780 
781  // If 'X' is a constant, and we transform, then we will immediately
782  // try to undo the fold, thus causing endless combine loop.
783  // So by default, let's assume everyone prefers the fold
784  // iff 'X' is not a constant.
785  return !XC;
786  }
787 
788  /// These two forms are equivalent:
789  /// sub %y, (xor %x, -1)
790  /// add (add %x, 1), %y
791  /// The variant with two add's is IR-canonical.
792  /// Some targets may prefer one to the other.
793  virtual bool preferIncOfAddToSubOfNot(EVT VT) const {
794  // By default, let's assume that everyone prefers the form with two add's.
795  return true;
796  }

799  virtual bool preferScalarizeSplat(unsigned Opc) const { return true; }

803  /// promotedInst1(...(promotedInstN(ext(load)))).
804  bool enableExtLdPromotion() const { return EnableExtLdPromotion; }

840  /// For targets without i1 registers, this gives the nature of the high-bits
841  /// of boolean values held in types wider than i1.
842  ///
843  /// "Boolean values" are special true/false values produced by nodes like
844  /// SETCC and consumed (as the condition) by nodes like SELECT and BRCOND.
845  /// Not to be confused with general values promoted from i1. Some cpus
846  /// distinguish between vectors of boolean and scalars; the isVec parameter
847  /// selects between the two kinds. For example on X86 a scalar boolean should
848  /// be zero extended from i1, while the elements of a vector of booleans
849  /// should be sign extended from i1.
850  ///
851  /// Some cpus also treat floating point types the same way as they treat
852  /// vectors instead of the way they treat scalars.
853  BooleanContent getBooleanContents(bool isVec, bool isFloat) const {
854  if (isVec)
855  return BooleanVectorContents;
856  return isFloat ? BooleanFloatContents : BooleanContents;
857  }
858 
859  BooleanContent getBooleanContents(EVT Type) const {
860  return getBooleanContents(Type.isVector(), Type.isFloatingPoint());
861  }
862 
863  /// Promote the given target boolean to a target boolean of the given type.
864  /// A target boolean is an integer value, not necessarily of type i1, the bits
865  /// of which conform to getBooleanContents.
866  ///
867  /// ValVT is the type of values that produced the boolean.
868  SDValue promoteTargetBoolean(SelectionDAG &DAG, SDValue Bool,
869  EVT ValVT) const {
870  SDLoc dl(Bool);
871  EVT BoolVT =
872  getSetCCResultType(DAG.getDataLayout(), *DAG.getContext(), ValVT);
873  ISD::NodeType ExtendCode = getExtendForContent(getBooleanContents(ValVT));
874  return DAG.getNode(ExtendCode, dl, BoolVT, Bool);
875  }

924  /// Return the preferred strategy to legalize tihs SHIFT instruction, with
925  /// \p ExpansionFactor being the recursion depth - how many expansion needed.
926  enum class ShiftLegalizationStrategy {
927  ExpandToParts,
928  ExpandThroughStack,
929  LowerToLibcall
930  };
931  virtual ShiftLegalizationStrategy
932  preferredShiftLegalizationStrategy(SelectionDAG &DAG, SDNode *N,
933  unsigned ExpansionFactor) const {
934  if (ExpansionFactor == 1)
935  return ShiftLegalizationStrategy::ExpandToParts;
936  return ShiftLegalizationStrategy::ExpandThroughStack;

939  /// Return true if the target has native support for the specified value type.
940  /// This means that it has a register that directly holds it without
941  /// promotions or expansions.
942  bool isTypeLegal(EVT VT) const {
943  assert(!VT.isSimple() ||
944  (unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy < std::size(RegClassForVT));
945  return VT.isSimple() && RegClassForVT[VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy] != nullptr;
946  }

948  class ValueTypeActionImpl {
949  /// ValueTypeActions - For each value type, keep a LegalizeTypeAction enum
950  /// that indicates how instruction selection should deal with the type.
951  LegalizeTypeAction ValueTypeActions[MVT::VALUETYPE_SIZE];
952 
953  public:
954  ValueTypeActionImpl() {
955  std::fill(std::begin(ValueTypeActions), std::end(ValueTypeActions),
956  TypeLegal);
957  }
958 
959  LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(MVT VT) const {
960  return ValueTypeActions[VT.SimpleTy];
961  }
962 
963  void setTypeAction(MVT VT, LegalizeTypeAction Action) {
964  ValueTypeActions[VT.SimpleTy] = Action;
965  }
966  };
967 
968  const ValueTypeActionImpl &getValueTypeActions() const {
969  return ValueTypeActions;
970  }
971 
972  /// Return pair that represents the legalization kind (first) that needs to
973  /// happen to EVT (second) in order to type-legalize it.
974  ///
975  /// First: how we should legalize values of this type, either it is already
976  /// legal (return 'Legal') or we need to promote it to a larger type (return
977  /// 'Promote'), or we need to expand it into multiple registers of smaller
978  /// integer type (return 'Expand'). 'Custom' is not an option.
979  ///
980  /// Second: for types supported by the target, this is an identity function.
981  /// For types that must be promoted to larger types, this returns the larger
982  /// type to promote to. For integer types that are larger than the largest
983  /// integer register, this contains one step in the expansion to get to the
984  /// smaller register. For illegal floating point types, this returns the
985  /// integer type to transform to.
986  LegalizeKind getTypeConversion(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const;
987 
988  /// Return how we should legalize values of this type, either it is already
989  /// legal (return 'Legal') or we need to promote it to a larger type (return
990  /// 'Promote'), or we need to expand it into multiple registers of smaller
991  /// integer type (return 'Expand'). 'Custom' is not an option.
992  LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
993  return getTypeConversion(Context, VT).first;
994  }
995  LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(MVT VT) const {
996  return ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(VT);
997  }
998 
999  /// For types supported by the target, this is an identity function. For
1000  /// types that must be promoted to larger types, this returns the larger type
1001  /// to promote to. For integer types that are larger than the largest integer
1002  /// register, this contains one step in the expansion to get to the smaller
1003  /// register. For illegal floating point types, this returns the integer type
1004  /// to transform to.
1005  virtual EVT getTypeToTransformTo(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
1006  return getTypeConversion(Context, VT).second;
1007  }
1008 
1009  /// For types supported by the target, this is an identity function. For
1010  /// types that must be expanded (i.e. integer types that are larger than the
1011  /// largest integer register or illegal floating point types), this returns
1012  /// the largest legal type it will be expanded to.
1013  EVT getTypeToExpandTo(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
1014  assert(!VT.isVector());
1015  while (true) {
1016  switch (getTypeAction(Context, VT)) {
1017  case TypeLegal:
1018  return VT;
1019  case TypeExpandInteger:
1020  VT = getTypeToTransformTo(Context, VT);
1021  break;
1022  default:
1023  llvm_unreachable("Type is not legal nor is it to be expanded!");
1024  }
1025  }
1026  }
1027 
1028  /// Vector types are broken down into some number of legal first class types.
1029  /// For example, EVT::v8f32 maps to 2 EVT::v4f32 with Altivec or SSE1, or 8
1030  /// promoted EVT::f64 values with the X86 FP stack. Similarly, EVT::v2i64
1031  /// turns into 4 EVT::i32 values with both PPC and X86.
1032  ///
1033  /// This method returns the number of registers needed, and the VT for each
1034  /// register. It also returns the VT and quantity of the intermediate values
1035  /// before they are promoted/expanded.
1036  unsigned getVectorTypeBreakdown(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT,
1037  EVT &IntermediateVT,
1038  unsigned &NumIntermediates,
1039  MVT &RegisterVT) const;
1040 
1041  /// Certain targets such as MIPS require that some types such as vectors are
1042  /// always broken down into scalars in some contexts. This occurs even if the
1043  /// vector type is legal.
1044  virtual unsigned getVectorTypeBreakdownForCallingConv(
1045  LLVMContext &Context, CallingConv::ID CC, EVT VT, EVT &IntermediateVT,
1046  unsigned &NumIntermediates, MVT &RegisterVT) const {
1047  return getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, IntermediateVT, NumIntermediates,
1048  RegisterVT);
1049  }

1059  // unknown address space.

1064  // (taken from memVT if zero)
1065  MaybeAlign align = Align(1); // alignment
1066 
1067  MachineMemOperand::Flags flags = MachineMemOperand::MONone;
1068  IntrinsicInfo() = default;

1111  /// How to legalize this custom operation?
1112  virtual LegalizeAction getCustomOperationAction(SDNode &Op) const {
1113  return Legal;
1114  }
1115 
1116  /// Return how this operation should be treated: either it is legal, needs to
1117  /// be promoted to a larger size, needs to be expanded to some other code
1118  /// sequence, or the target has a custom expander for it.
1119  LegalizeAction getOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
1120  if (VT.isExtended()) return Expand;
1121  // If a target-specific SDNode requires legalization, require the target
1122  // to provide custom legalization for it.
1123  if (Op >= std::size(OpActions[0]))
1124  return Custom;
1125  return OpActions[(unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy][Op];
1126  }
1127 
1128  /// Custom method defined by each target to indicate if an operation which
1129  /// may require a scale is supported natively by the target.
1130  /// If not, the operation is illegal.
1131  virtual bool isSupportedFixedPointOperation(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
1132  unsigned Scale) const {
1133  return false;
1134  }
1135 
1136  /// Some fixed point operations may be natively supported by the target but
1137  /// only for specific scales. This method allows for checking
1138  /// if the width is supported by the target for a given operation that may
1139  /// depend on scale.
1140  LegalizeAction getFixedPointOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
1141  unsigned Scale) const {
1142  auto Action = getOperationAction(Op, VT);
1143  if (Action != Legal)
1144  return Action;
1145 
1146  // This operation is supported in this type but may only work on specific
1147  // scales.
1148  bool Supported;
1149  switch (Op) {
1150  default:
1151  llvm_unreachable("Unexpected fixed point operation.");
1152  case ISD::SMULFIX:
1153  case ISD::SMULFIXSAT:
1154  case ISD::UMULFIX:
1155  case ISD::UMULFIXSAT:
1156  case ISD::SDIVFIX:
1157  case ISD::SDIVFIXSAT:
1158  case ISD::UDIVFIX:
1159  case ISD::UDIVFIXSAT:
1160  Supported = isSupportedFixedPointOperation(Op, VT, Scale);
1161  break;
1162  }
1163 
1164  return Supported ? Action : Expand;
1165  }
1166 
1167  // If Op is a strict floating-point operation, return the result
1168  // of getOperationAction for the equivalent non-strict operation.
1169  LegalizeAction getStrictFPOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
1170  unsigned EqOpc;
1171  switch (Op) {
1172  default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected FP pseudo-opcode");
1173 #define DAG_INSTRUCTION(NAME, NARG, ROUND_MODE, INTRINSIC, DAGN) \
1174  case ISD::STRICT_##DAGN: EqOpc = ISD::DAGN; break;
1175 #define CMP_INSTRUCTION(NAME, NARG, ROUND_MODE, INTRINSIC, DAGN) \
1176  case ISD::STRICT_##DAGN: EqOpc = ISD::SETCC; break;
1177 #include "llvm/IR/ConstrainedOps.def"
1178  }
1179 
1180  return getOperationAction(EqOpc, VT);
1181  }
1182 
1183  /// Return true if the specified operation is legal on this target or can be
1184  /// made legal with custom lowering. This is used to help guide high-level
1185  /// lowering decisions. LegalOnly is an optional convenience for code paths
1186  /// traversed pre and post legalisation.
1187  bool isOperationLegalOrCustom(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
1188  bool LegalOnly = false) const {
1189  if (LegalOnly)
1190  return isOperationLegal(Op, VT);
1191 
1192  return (VT == MVT::Other || isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
1193  (getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Legal ||
1194  getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Custom);
1195  }
1196 
1197  /// Return true if the specified operation is legal on this target or can be
1198  /// made legal using promotion. This is used to help guide high-level lowering
1199  /// decisions. LegalOnly is an optional convenience for code paths traversed
1200  /// pre and post legalisation.
1201  bool isOperationLegalOrPromote(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
1202  bool LegalOnly = false) const {
1203  if (LegalOnly)
1204  return isOperationLegal(Op, VT);
1205 
1206  return (VT == MVT::Other || isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
1207  (getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Legal ||
1208  getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Promote);
1209  }
1210 
1211  /// Return true if the specified operation is legal on this target or can be
1212  /// made legal with custom lowering or using promotion. This is used to help
1213  /// guide high-level lowering decisions. LegalOnly is an optional convenience
1214  /// for code paths traversed pre and post legalisation.
1215  bool isOperationLegalOrCustomOrPromote(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
1216  bool LegalOnly = false) const {
1217  if (LegalOnly)
1218  return isOperationLegal(Op, VT);
1219 
1220  return (VT == MVT::Other || isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
1221  (getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Legal ||
1222  getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Custom ||
1223  getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Promote);
1224  }
1225 
1226  /// Return true if the operation uses custom lowering, regardless of whether
1227  /// the type is legal or not.
1228  bool isOperationCustom(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
1229  return getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Custom;
1230  }
1231 
1232  /// Return true if lowering to a jump table is allowed.
1233  virtual bool areJTsAllowed(const Function *Fn) const {
1234  if (Fn->getFnAttribute("no-jump-tables").getValueAsBool())
1235  return false;
1236 
1237  return isOperationLegalOrCustom(ISD::BR_JT, MVT::Other) ||
1238  isOperationLegalOrCustom(ISD::BRIND, MVT::Other);
1239  }
1240 
1241  /// Check whether the range [Low,High] fits in a machine word.
1242  bool rangeFitsInWord(const APInt &Low, const APInt &High,
1243  const DataLayout &DL) const {
1244  // FIXME: Using the pointer type doesn't seem ideal.
1245  uint64_t BW = DL.getIndexSizeInBits(0u);
1246  uint64_t Range = (High - Low).getLimitedValue(UINT64_MAX - 1) + 1;
1247  return Range <= BW;
1248  }
1249 
1250  /// Return true if lowering to a jump table is suitable for a set of case
1251  /// clusters which may contain \p NumCases cases, \p Range range of values.
1252  virtual bool isSuitableForJumpTable(const SwitchInst *SI, uint64_t NumCases,
1253  uint64_t Range, ProfileSummaryInfo *PSI,
1254  BlockFrequencyInfo *BFI) const;
1255 
1256  /// Returns preferred type for switch condition.
1257  virtual MVT getPreferredSwitchConditionType(LLVMContext &Context,
1258  EVT ConditionVT) const;
1259 
1260  /// Return true if lowering to a bit test is suitable for a set of case
1261  /// clusters which contains \p NumDests unique destinations, \p Low and
1262  /// \p High as its lowest and highest case values, and expects \p NumCmps
1263  /// case value comparisons. Check if the number of destinations, comparison
1264  /// metric, and range are all suitable.
1265  bool isSuitableForBitTests(unsigned NumDests, unsigned NumCmps,
1266  const APInt &Low, const APInt &High,
1267  const DataLayout &DL) const {
1268  // FIXME: I don't think NumCmps is the correct metric: a single case and a
1269  // range of cases both require only one branch to lower. Just looking at the
1270  // number of clusters and destinations should be enough to decide whether to
1271  // build bit tests.
1272 
1273  // To lower a range with bit tests, the range must fit the bitwidth of a
1274  // machine word.
1275  if (!rangeFitsInWord(Low, High, DL))
1276  return false;
1277 
1278  // Decide whether it's profitable to lower this range with bit tests. Each
1279  // destination requires a bit test and branch, and there is an overall range
1280  // check branch. For a small number of clusters, separate comparisons might
1281  // be cheaper, and for many destinations, splitting the range might be
1282  // better.
1283  return (NumDests == 1 && NumCmps >= 3) || (NumDests == 2 && NumCmps >= 5) ||
1284  (NumDests == 3 && NumCmps >= 6);
1285  }
1286 
1287  /// Return true if the specified operation is illegal on this target or
1288  /// unlikely to be made legal with custom lowering. This is used to help guide
1289  /// high-level lowering decisions.
1290  bool isOperationExpand(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
1291  return (!isTypeLegal(VT) || getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Expand);
1292  }
1293 
1294  /// Return true if the specified operation is legal on this target.
1295  bool isOperationLegal(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
1296  return (VT == MVT::Other || isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
1297  getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Legal;
1298  }

1300  /// Return how this load with extension should be treated: either it is legal,
1301  /// needs to be promoted to a larger size, needs to be expanded to some other
1302  /// code sequence, or the target has a custom expander for it.
1303  LegalizeAction getLoadExtAction(unsigned ExtType, EVT ValVT,
1304  EVT MemVT) const {
1305  if (ValVT.isExtended() || MemVT.isExtended()) return Expand;
1306  unsigned ValI = (unsigned) ValVT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy;
1307  unsigned MemI = (unsigned) MemVT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy;
1308  assert(ExtType < ISD::LAST_LOADEXT_TYPE && ValI < MVT::VALUETYPE_SIZE &&
1309  MemI < MVT::VALUETYPE_SIZE && "Table isn't big enough!");
1310  unsigned Shift = 4 * ExtType;
1311  return (LegalizeAction)((LoadExtActions[ValI][MemI] >> Shift) & 0xf);
1312  }
1313 
1314  /// Return true if the specified load with extension is legal on this target.
1315  bool isLoadExtLegal(unsigned ExtType, EVT ValVT, EVT MemVT) const {
1316  return getLoadExtAction(ExtType, ValVT, MemVT) == Legal;
1317  }
1318 
1319  /// Return true if the specified load with extension is legal or custom
1320  /// on this target.
1321  bool isLoadExtLegalOrCustom(unsigned ExtType, EVT ValVT, EVT MemVT) const {
1322  return getLoadExtAction(ExtType, ValVT, MemVT) == Legal ||
1323  getLoadExtAction(ExtType, ValVT, MemVT) == Custom;
1324  }

1326  /// Return how this store with truncation should be treated: either it is
1327  /// legal, needs to be promoted to a larger size, needs to be expanded to some
1328  /// other code sequence, or the target has a custom expander for it.
1329  LegalizeAction getTruncStoreAction(EVT ValVT, EVT MemVT) const {
1330  if (ValVT.isExtended() || MemVT.isExtended()) return Expand;
1331  unsigned ValI = (unsigned) ValVT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy;
1332  unsigned MemI = (unsigned) MemVT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy;
1333  assert(ValI < MVT::VALUETYPE_SIZE && MemI < MVT::VALUETYPE_SIZE &&
1334  "Table isn't big enough!");
1335  return TruncStoreActions[ValI][MemI];
1336  }
1337 
1338  /// Return true if the specified store with truncation is legal on this
1339  /// target.
1340  bool isTruncStoreLegal(EVT ValVT, EVT MemVT) const {
1341  return isTypeLegal(ValVT) && getTruncStoreAction(ValVT, MemVT) == Legal;
1342  }
1343 
1344  /// Return true if the specified store with truncation has solution on this
1345  /// target.
1346  bool isTruncStoreLegalOrCustom(EVT ValVT, EVT MemVT) const {
1347  return isTypeLegal(ValVT) &&
1348  (getTruncStoreAction(ValVT, MemVT) == Legal ||
1349  getTruncStoreAction(ValVT, MemVT) == Custom);
1350  }

1354  if (LegalOnly)
1355  return isTruncStoreLegal(ValVT, MemVT);
1356 
1357  return isTruncStoreLegalOrCustom(ValVT, MemVT);
1358  }

1426  // Return true if the target supports a scatter/gather instruction with
1427  // indices which are scaled by the particular value. Note that all targets
1428  // must by definition support scale of 1.
1429  virtual bool isLegalScaleForGatherScatter(uint64_t Scale,
1430  uint64_t ElemSize) const {
1431  // MGATHER/MSCATTER are only required to support scaling by one or by the
1432  // element size.

1434  return false;

1438  /// Return how the condition code should be treated: either it is legal, needs
1439  /// to be expanded to some other code sequence, or the target has a custom
1440  /// expander for it.
1441  LegalizeAction
1442  getCondCodeAction(ISD::CondCode CC, MVT VT) const {
1443  assert((unsigned)CC < std::size(CondCodeActions) &&
1444  ((unsigned)VT.SimpleTy >> 3) < std::size(CondCodeActions[0]) &&
1445  "Table isn't big enough!");
1446  // See setCondCodeAction for how this is encoded.
1447  uint32_t Shift = 4 * (VT.SimpleTy & 0x7);
1448  uint32_t Value = CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3];
1449  LegalizeAction Action = (LegalizeAction) ((Value >> Shift) & 0xF);
1450  assert(Action != Promote && "Can't promote condition code!");
1451  return Action;
1452  }
1453 
1454  /// Return true if the specified condition code is legal on this target.
1455  bool isCondCodeLegal(ISD::CondCode CC, MVT VT) const {
1456  return getCondCodeAction(CC, VT) == Legal;
1457  }
1458 
1459  /// Return true if the specified condition code is legal or custom on this
1460  /// target.
1461  bool isCondCodeLegalOrCustom(ISD::CondCode CC, MVT VT) const {
1462  return getCondCodeAction(CC, VT) == Legal ||
1463  getCondCodeAction(CC, VT) == Custom;
1464  }
1465 
1466  /// If the action for this operation is to promote, this method returns the
1467  /// ValueType to promote to.
1468  MVT getTypeToPromoteTo(unsigned Op, MVT VT) const {
1469  assert(getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Promote &&
1470  "This operation isn't promoted!");
1471 
1472  // See if this has an explicit type specified.
1473  std::map<std::pair<unsigned, MVT::SimpleValueType>,
1474  MVT::SimpleValueType>::const_iterator PTTI =
1475  PromoteToType.find(std::make_pair(Op, VT.SimpleTy));
1476  if (PTTI != PromoteToType.end()) return PTTI->second;
1477 
1478  assert((VT.isInteger() || VT.isFloatingPoint()) &&
1479  "Cannot autopromote this type, add it with AddPromotedToType.");
1480 
1481  MVT NVT = VT;
1482  do {
1483  NVT = (MVT::SimpleValueType)(NVT.SimpleTy+1);
1484  assert(NVT.isInteger() == VT.isInteger() && NVT != MVT::isVoid &&
1485  "Didn't find type to promote to!");
1486  } while (!isTypeLegal(NVT) ||
1487  getOperationAction(Op, NVT) == Promote);
1488  return NVT;
1489  }

1491  virtual EVT getAsmOperandValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1492  bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1493  return getValueType(DL, Ty, AllowUnknown);
1494  }
1495 
1496  /// Return the EVT corresponding to this LLVM type. This is fixed by the LLVM
1497  /// operations except for the pointer size. If AllowUnknown is true, this
1498  /// will return MVT::Other for types with no EVT counterpart (e.g. structs),
1499  /// otherwise it will assert.
1500  EVT getValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1501  bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1502  // Lower scalar pointers to native pointer types.
1503  if (auto *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Ty))
1504  return getPointerTy(DL, PTy->getAddressSpace());
1505 
1506  if (auto *VTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1507  Type *EltTy = VTy->getElementType();
1508  // Lower vectors of pointers to native pointer types.
1509  if (auto *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(EltTy)) {
1510  EVT PointerTy(getPointerTy(DL, PTy->getAddressSpace()));
1511  EltTy = PointerTy.getTypeForEVT(Ty->getContext());
1512  }
1513  return EVT::getVectorVT(Ty->getContext(), EVT::getEVT(EltTy, false),
1514  VTy->getElementCount());
1515  }
1516 
1517  return EVT::getEVT(Ty, AllowUnknown);
1518  }
1519 
1520  EVT getMemValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1521  bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1522  // Lower scalar pointers to native pointer types.
1523  if (PointerType *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Ty))
1524  return getPointerMemTy(DL, PTy->getAddressSpace());
1525  else if (VectorType *VTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1526  Type *Elm = VTy->getElementType();
1527  if (PointerType *PT = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Elm)) {
1528  EVT PointerTy(getPointerMemTy(DL, PT->getAddressSpace()));
1529  Elm = PointerTy.getTypeForEVT(Ty->getContext());
1530  }
1531  return EVT::getVectorVT(Ty->getContext(), EVT::getEVT(Elm, false),
1532  VTy->getElementCount());
1533  }
1534 
1535  return getValueType(DL, Ty, AllowUnknown);
1536  }
1537 
1538 
1539  /// Return the MVT corresponding to this LLVM type. See getValueType.
1540  MVT getSimpleValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1541  bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1542  return getValueType(DL, Ty, AllowUnknown).getSimpleVT();
1543  }

1546  /// arguments in the caller parameter area. This is the actual alignment, not

1548  virtual uint64_t getByValTypeAlignment(Type *Ty, const DataLayout &DL) const;

1550  /// Return the type of registers that this ValueType will eventually require.
1551  MVT getRegisterType(MVT VT) const {
1552  assert((unsigned)VT.SimpleTy < std::size(RegisterTypeForVT));
1553  return RegisterTypeForVT[VT.SimpleTy];
1554  }
1555 
1556  /// Return the type of registers that this ValueType will eventually require.
1557  MVT getRegisterType(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
1558  if (VT.isSimple())
1559  return getRegisterType(VT.getSimpleVT());
1560  if (VT.isVector()) {
1561  EVT VT1;
1562  MVT RegisterVT;
1563  unsigned NumIntermediates;
1564  (void)getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, VT1,
1565  NumIntermediates, RegisterVT);
1566  return RegisterVT;
1567  }
1568  if (VT.isInteger()) {
1569  return getRegisterType(Context, getTypeToTransformTo(Context, VT));
1570  }
1571  llvm_unreachable("Unsupported extended type!");
1572  }
1573 
1574  /// Return the number of registers that this ValueType will eventually
1575  /// require.
1576  ///
1577  /// This is one for any types promoted to live in larger registers, but may be
1578  /// more than one for types (like i64) that are split into pieces. For types
1579  /// like i140, which are first promoted then expanded, it is the number of
1580  /// registers needed to hold all the bits of the original type. For an i140
1581  /// on a 32 bit machine this means 5 registers.
1582  ///
1583  /// RegisterVT may be passed as a way to override the default settings, for
1584  /// instance with i128 inline assembly operands on SystemZ.
1585  virtual unsigned
1586  getNumRegisters(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT,
1587  std::optional<MVT> RegisterVT = std::nullopt) const {
1588  if (VT.isSimple()) {
1589  assert((unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy <
1590  std::size(NumRegistersForVT));
1591  return NumRegistersForVT[VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy];
1592  }
1593  if (VT.isVector()) {
1594  EVT VT1;
1595  MVT VT2;
1596  unsigned NumIntermediates;
1597  return getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, VT1, NumIntermediates, VT2);
1598  }
1599  if (VT.isInteger()) {
1600  unsigned BitWidth = VT.getSizeInBits();
1601  unsigned RegWidth = getRegisterType(Context, VT).getSizeInBits();
1602  return (BitWidth + RegWidth - 1) / RegWidth;
1603  }
1604  llvm_unreachable("Unsupported extended type!");
1605  }
1606 
1607  /// Certain combinations of ABIs, Targets and features require that types
1608  /// are legal for some operations and not for other operations.
1609  /// For MIPS all vector types must be passed through the integer register set.
1610  virtual MVT getRegisterTypeForCallingConv(LLVMContext &Context,
1611  CallingConv::ID CC, EVT VT) const {
1612  return getRegisterType(Context, VT);
1613  }

1615  /// Certain targets require unusual breakdowns of certain types. For MIPS,
1616  /// this occurs when a vector type is used, as vector are passed through the
1617  /// integer register set.
1618  virtual unsigned getNumRegistersForCallingConv(LLVMContext &Context,
1619  CallingConv::ID CC,
1620  EVT VT) const {
1621  return getNumRegisters(Context, VT);
1622  }

1636  /// Return true if it is profitable to reduce a load to a smaller type.
1637  /// Example: (i16 (trunc (i32 (load x))) -> i16 load x
1638  virtual bool shouldReduceLoadWidth(SDNode *Load, ISD::LoadExtType ExtTy,
1639  EVT NewVT) const {
1640  // By default, assume that it is cheaper to extract a subvector from a wide
1641  // vector load rather than creating multiple narrow vector loads.
1642  if (NewVT.isVector() && !Load->hasOneUse())
1643  return false;
1644 
1645  return true;
1646  }

1720  /// Determine if the target supports unaligned memory accesses.
1721  ///
1722  /// This function returns true if the target allows unaligned memory accesses
1723  /// of the specified type in the given address space. If true, it also returns
1724  /// a relative speed of the unaligned memory access in the last argument by
1725  /// reference. The higher the speed number the faster the operation comparing
1726  /// to a number returned by another such call. This is used, for example, in
1727  /// situations where an array copy/move/set is converted to a sequence of
1728  /// store operations. Its use helps to ensure that such replacements don't

1996  /// Perform a load-linked operation on Addr, returning a "Value *" with the

2051  /// is not responsible for masking and shifting the result.
2052  virtual Value *emitMaskedAtomicCmpXchgIntrinsic(

2057 
2058  /// Inserts in the IR a target-specific intrinsic specifying a fence.
2059  /// It is called by AtomicExpandPass before expanding an
2060  /// AtomicRMW/AtomicCmpXchg/AtomicStore/AtomicLoad
2061  /// if shouldInsertFencesForAtomic returns true.
2062  ///
2063  /// Inst is the original atomic instruction, prior to other expansions that
2064  /// may be performed.
2065  ///
2066  /// This function should either return a nullptr, or a pointer to an IR-level
2067  /// Instruction*. Even complex fence sequences can be represented by a
2068  /// single Instruction* through an intrinsic to be lowered later.
2069  /// Backends should override this method to produce target-specific intrinsic
2070  /// for their fences.
2071  /// FIXME: Please note that the default implementation here in terms of
2072  /// IR-level fences exists for historical/compatibility reasons and is
2073  /// *unsound* ! Fences cannot, in general, be used to restore sequential
2074  /// consistency. For example, consider the following example:
2075  /// atomic<int> x = y = 0;
2076  /// int r1, r2, r3, r4;
2077  /// Thread 0:
2078  /// x.store(1);
2079  /// Thread 1:
2080  /// y.store(1);
2081  /// Thread 2:
2082  /// r1 = x.load();
2083  /// r2 = y.load();
2084  /// Thread 3:
2085  /// r3 = y.load();
2086  /// r4 = x.load();
2087  /// r1 = r3 = 1 and r2 = r4 = 0 is impossible as long as the accesses are all
2088  /// seq_cst. But if they are lowered to monotonic accesses, no amount of
2089  /// IR-level fences can prevent it.
2090  /// @{
2091  virtual Instruction *emitLeadingFence(IRBuilderBase &Builder,
2092  Instruction *Inst,
2093  AtomicOrdering Ord) const;
2094 
2095  virtual Instruction *emitTrailingFence(IRBuilderBase &Builder,
2096  Instruction *Inst,
2097  AtomicOrdering Ord) const;
2098  /// @}

2100  // Emits code that executes when the comparison result in the ll/sc

2102  // not execute. This makes it possible to balance out the load-linked with
2103  // a dedicated instruction, if desired.
2104  // E.g., on ARM, if ldrex isn't followed by strex, the exclusive monitor would
2105  // be unnecessarily held, except if clrex, inserted by this hook, is executed.
2106  virtual void emitAtomicCmpXchgNoStoreLLBalance(IRBuilderBase &Builder) const {}

2162  /// Returns how the given atomic atomicrmw should be cast by the IR-level
2163  /// AtomicExpand pass.
2164  virtual AtomicExpansionKind
2165  shouldCastAtomicRMWIInIR(AtomicRMWInst *RMWI) const {
2166  if (RMWI->getOperation() == AtomicRMWInst::Xchg &&
2167  (RMWI->getValOperand()->getType()->isFloatingPointTy() ||
2168  RMWI->getValOperand()->getType()->isPointerTy()))
2169  return AtomicExpansionKind::CastToInteger;
2170 
2171  return AtomicExpansionKind::None;
2172  }

2174  /// On some platforms, an AtomicRMW that never actually modifies the value
2175  /// (such as fetch_add of 0) can be turned into a fence followed by an
2176  /// atomic load. This may sound useless, but it makes it possible for the
2177  /// processor to keep the cacheline shared, dramatically improving
2178  /// performance. And such idempotent RMWs are useful for implementing some
2179  /// kinds of locks, see for example (justification + benchmarks):
2180  /// http://www.hpl.hp.com/techreports/2012/HPL-2012-68.pdf
2181  /// This method tries doing that transformation, returning the atomic load if
2182  /// it succeeds, and nullptr otherwise.
2183  /// If shouldExpandAtomicLoadInIR returns true on that load, it will undergo
2184  /// another round of expansion.
2185  virtual LoadInst *
2186  lowerIdempotentRMWIntoFencedLoad(AtomicRMWInst *RMWI) const {
2187  return nullptr;
2188  }

2191  /// SIGN_EXTEND, or ANY_EXTEND).
2192  virtual ISD::NodeType getExtendForAtomicOps() const {
2193  return ISD::ZERO_EXTEND;
2194  }
2195 
2196  /// Returns how the platform's atomic compare and swap expects its comparison
2197  /// value to be extended (ZERO_EXTEND, SIGN_EXTEND, or ANY_EXTEND). This is
2198  /// separate from getExtendForAtomicOps, which is concerned with the
2199  /// sign-extension of the instruction's output, whereas here we are concerned
2200  /// with the sign-extension of the input. For targets with compare-and-swap
2201  /// instructions (or sub-word comparisons in their LL/SC loop expansions),
2202  /// the input can be ANY_EXTEND, but the output will still have a specific
2203  /// extension.
2204  virtual ISD::NodeType getExtendForAtomicCmpSwapArg() const {
2205  return ISD::ANY_EXTEND;
2206  }

2210  /// Returns true if we should normalize
2211  /// select(N0&N1, X, Y) => select(N0, select(N1, X, Y), Y) and
2212  /// select(N0|N1, X, Y) => select(N0, select(N1, X, Y, Y)) if it is likely
2213  /// that it saves us from materializing N0 and N1 in an integer register.
2214  /// Targets that are able to perform and/or on flags should return false here.
2215  virtual bool shouldNormalizeToSelectSequence(LLVMContext &Context,
2216  EVT VT) const {
2217  // If a target has multiple condition registers, then it likely has logical
2218  // operations on those registers.
2219  if (hasMultipleConditionRegisters())
2220  return false;
2221  // Only do the transform if the value won't be split into multiple
2222  // registers.
2223  LegalizeTypeAction Action = getTypeAction(Context, VT);
2224  return Action != TypeExpandInteger && Action != TypeExpandFloat &&
2225  Action != TypeSplitVector;
2226  }

2249  /// This may not be true if c1 and c2 can be represented as immediates but
2250  /// c1*c2 cannot, for example.
2251  /// The target should check if c1, c2 and c1*c2 can be represented as
2252  /// immediates, or have to be materialized into registers. If it is not sure
2253  /// about some cases, a default true can be returned to let the DAGCombiner

2261  /// Return true if it is more correct/profitable to use strict FP_TO_INT
2262  /// conversion operations - canonicalizing the FP source value instead of

2271  /// Return true if it is beneficial to expand an @llvm.powi.* intrinsic.
2272  /// If not optimizing for size, expanding @llvm.powi.* intrinsics is always
2273  /// considered beneficial.
2274  /// If optimizing for size, expansion is only considered beneficial for upto
2275  /// 5 multiplies and a divide (if the exponent is negative).
2276  bool isBeneficialToExpandPowI(int Exponent, bool OptForSize) const {
2277  if (Exponent < 0)
2278  Exponent = -Exponent;
2279  return !OptForSize ||
2280  (llvm::popcount((unsigned int)Exponent) + Log2_32(Exponent) < 7);
2281  }

2283  //===--------------------------------------------------------------------===//
2284  // TargetLowering Configuration Methods - These methods should be invoked by
2285  // the derived class constructor to configure this object for the target.
2286  //
2287 protected:
2288  /// Specify how the target extends the result of integer and floating point

2388  /// Indicate that the specified load with extension does not work with the
2389  /// specified type and indicate what to do about it.
2390  void setLoadExtAction(unsigned ExtType, MVT ValVT, MVT MemVT,
2391  LegalizeAction Action) {
2392  assert(ExtType < ISD::LAST_LOADEXT_TYPE && ValVT.isValid() &&
2393  MemVT.isValid() && "Table isn't big enough!");
2394  assert((unsigned)Action < 0x10 && "too many bits for bitfield array");
2395  unsigned Shift = 4 * ExtType;
2396  LoadExtActions[ValVT.SimpleTy][MemVT.SimpleTy] &= ~((uint16_t)0xF << Shift);
2397  LoadExtActions[ValVT.SimpleTy][MemVT.SimpleTy] |= (uint16_t)Action << Shift;
2398  }

2400  LegalizeAction Action) {

2402  setLoadExtAction(ExtType, ValVT, MemVT, Action);
2403  }

2471  /// Indicate that the specified condition code is or isn't supported on the
2472  /// target and indicate what to do about it.
2473  void setCondCodeAction(ArrayRef<ISD::CondCode> CCs, MVT VT,
2474  LegalizeAction Action) {
2475  for (auto CC : CCs) {
2476  assert(VT.isValid() && (unsigned)CC < std::size(CondCodeActions) &&
2477  "Table isn't big enough!");
2478  assert((unsigned)Action < 0x10 && "too many bits for bitfield array");
2479  /// The lower 3 bits of the SimpleTy index into Nth 4bit set from the
2480  /// 32-bit value and the upper 29 bits index into the second dimension of
2481  /// the array to select what 32-bit value to use.
2482  uint32_t Shift = 4 * (VT.SimpleTy & 0x7);
2483  CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3] &= ~((uint32_t)0xF << Shift);
2484  CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3] |= (uint32_t)Action << Shift;
2485  }
2486  }
2487  void setCondCodeAction(ArrayRef<ISD::CondCode> CCs, ArrayRef<MVT> VTs,
2488  LegalizeAction Action) {
2489  for (auto VT : VTs)
2490  setCondCodeAction(CCs, VT, Action);
2491  }

2496  /// the default.
2497  void AddPromotedToType(unsigned Opc, MVT OrigVT, MVT DestVT) {
2498  PromoteToType[std::make_pair(Opc, OrigVT.SimpleTy)] = DestVT.SimpleTy;

2577  /// CodeGenPrepare sinks address calculations into the same BB as Load/Store
2578  /// instructions reading the address. This allows as much computation as
2579  /// possible to be done in the address mode for that operand. This hook lets
2580  /// targets also pass back when this should be done on intrinsics which
2581  /// load/store.
2582  virtual bool getAddrModeArguments(IntrinsicInst * /*I*/,
2583  SmallVectorImpl<Value*> &/*Ops*/,
2584  Type *&/*AccessTy*/) const {
2585  return false;
2586  }
2587 
2588  /// This represents an addressing mode of:
2589  /// BaseGV + BaseOffs + BaseReg + Scale*ScaleReg
2590  /// If BaseGV is null, there is no BaseGV.
2591  /// If BaseOffs is zero, there is no base offset.
2592  /// If HasBaseReg is false, there is no base register.
2593  /// If Scale is zero, there is no ScaleReg. Scale of 1 indicates a reg with
2594  /// no scale.
2595  struct AddrMode {
2596  GlobalValue *BaseGV = nullptr;
2597  int64_t BaseOffs = 0;
2598  bool HasBaseReg = false;
2599  int64_t Scale = 0;
2600  AddrMode() = default;
2601  };
2602 
2603  /// Return true if the addressing mode represented by AM is legal for this
2604  /// target, for a load/store of the specified type.
2605  ///
2606  /// The type may be VoidTy, in which case only return true if the addressing
2607  /// mode is legal for a load/store of any legal type. TODO: Handle
2608  /// pre/postinc as well.
2609  ///
2610  /// If the address space cannot be determined, it will be -1.
2611  ///
2612  /// TODO: Remove default argument
2613  virtual bool isLegalAddressingMode(const DataLayout &DL, const AddrMode &AM,
2614  Type *Ty, unsigned AddrSpace,
2615  Instruction *I = nullptr) const;

2645  return false;

2658  /// or bitcast to type 'To', return true if the set should be converted to

2662  (To->isIntegerTy() || To->isFloatingPointTy());

2665  /// Returns true if the opcode is a commutative binary operation.
2666  virtual bool isCommutativeBinOp(unsigned Opcode) const {
2667  // FIXME: This should get its info from the td file.
2668  switch (Opcode) {
2669  case ISD::ADD:
2670  case ISD::SMIN:
2671  case ISD::SMAX:
2672  case ISD::UMIN:
2673  case ISD::UMAX:
2674  case ISD::MUL:
2675  case ISD::MULHU:
2676  case ISD::MULHS:
2677  case ISD::SMUL_LOHI:
2678  case ISD::UMUL_LOHI:
2679  case ISD::FADD:
2680  case ISD::FMUL:
2681  case ISD::AND:
2682  case ISD::OR:
2683  case ISD::XOR:
2684  case ISD::SADDO:
2685  case ISD::UADDO:
2686  case ISD::ADDC:
2687  case ISD::ADDE:
2688  case ISD::SADDSAT:
2689  case ISD::UADDSAT:
2690  case ISD::FMINNUM:
2691  case ISD::FMAXNUM:
2692  case ISD::FMINNUM_IEEE:
2693  case ISD::FMAXNUM_IEEE:
2694  case ISD::FMINIMUM:
2695  case ISD::FMAXIMUM:
2696  case ISD::AVGFLOORS:
2697  case ISD::AVGFLOORU:
2698  case ISD::AVGCEILS:
2699  case ISD::AVGCEILU:
2700  case ISD::ABDS:
2701  case ISD::ABDU:
2702  return true;
2703  default: return false;
2704  }
2705  }
2706 
2707  /// Return true if the node is a math/logic binary operator.
2708  virtual bool isBinOp(unsigned Opcode) const {
2709  // A commutative binop must be a binop.
2710  if (isCommutativeBinOp(Opcode))
2711  return true;
2712  // These are non-commutative binops.
2713  switch (Opcode) {
2714  case ISD::SUB:
2715  case ISD::SHL:
2716  case ISD::SRL:
2717  case ISD::SRA:
2718  case ISD::ROTL:
2719  case ISD::ROTR:
2720  case ISD::SDIV:
2721  case ISD::UDIV:
2722  case ISD::SREM:
2723  case ISD::UREM:
2724  case ISD::SSUBSAT:
2725  case ISD::USUBSAT:
2726  case ISD::FSUB:
2727  case ISD::FDIV:
2728  case ISD::FREM:
2729  return true;
2730  default:
2731  return false;
2732  }
2733  }

2735  /// Return true if it's free to truncate a value of type FromTy to type
2736  /// ToTy. e.g. On x86 it's free to truncate a i32 value in register EAX to i16
2737  /// by referencing its sub-register AX.
2738  /// Targets must return false when FromTy <= ToTy.
2739  virtual bool isTruncateFree(Type *FromTy, Type *ToTy) const {
2740  return false;
2741  }
2742 
2743  /// Return true if a truncation from FromTy to ToTy is permitted when deciding
2744  /// whether a call is in tail position. Typically this means that both results
2745  /// would be assigned to the same register or stack slot, but it could mean
2746  /// the target performs adequate checks of its own before proceeding with the
2747  /// tail call. Targets must return false when FromTy <= ToTy.
2748  virtual bool allowTruncateForTailCall(Type *FromTy, Type *ToTy) const {
2749  return false;
2750  }

2752  virtual bool isTruncateFree(EVT FromVT, EVT ToVT) const { return false; }
2753  virtual bool isTruncateFree(LLT FromTy, LLT ToTy, const DataLayout &DL,
2754  LLVMContext &Ctx) const {
2755  return isTruncateFree(getApproximateEVTForLLT(FromTy, DL, Ctx),
2756  getApproximateEVTForLLT(ToTy, DL, Ctx));
2757  }

2759  virtual bool isProfitableToHoist(Instruction *I) const { return true; }
2760 
2761  /// Return true if the extension represented by \p I is free.
2762  /// Unlikely the is[Z|FP]ExtFree family which is based on types,
2763  /// this method can use the context provided by \p I to decide
2764  /// whether or not \p I is free.
2765  /// This method extends the behavior of the is[Z|FP]ExtFree family.
2766  /// In other words, if is[Z|FP]Free returns true, then this method
2767  /// returns true as well. The converse is not true.
2768  /// The target can perform the adequate checks by overriding isExtFreeImpl.
2769  /// \pre \p I must be a sign, zero, or fp extension.
2770  bool isExtFree(const Instruction *I) const {
2771  switch (I->getOpcode()) {
2772  case Instruction::FPExt:
2773  if (isFPExtFree(EVT::getEVT(I->getType()),
2774  EVT::getEVT(I->getOperand(0)->getType())))
2775  return true;
2776  break;
2777  case Instruction::ZExt:
2778  if (isZExtFree(I->getOperand(0)->getType(), I->getType()))
2779  return true;
2780  break;
2781  case Instruction::SExt:
2782  break;
2783  default:
2784  llvm_unreachable("Instruction is not an extension");
2785  }
2786  return isExtFreeImpl(I);
2787  }
2788 
2789  /// Return true if \p Load and \p Ext can form an ExtLoad.
2790  /// For example, in AArch64
2791  /// %L = load i8, i8* %ptr
2792  /// %E = zext i8 %L to i32
2793  /// can be lowered into one load instruction
2794  /// ldrb w0, [x0]
2795  bool isExtLoad(const LoadInst *Load, const Instruction *Ext,
2796  const DataLayout &DL) const {
2797  EVT VT = getValueType(DL, Ext->getType());
2798  EVT LoadVT = getValueType(DL, Load->getType());
2799 
2800  // If the load has other users and the truncate is not free, the ext
2801  // probably isn't free.
2802  if (!Load->hasOneUse() && (isTypeLegal(LoadVT) || !isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
2803  !isTruncateFree(Ext->getType(), Load->getType()))
2804  return false;
2805 
2806  // Check whether the target supports casts folded into loads.
2807  unsigned LType;
2808  if (isa<ZExtInst>(Ext))
2809  LType = ISD::ZEXTLOAD;
2810  else {
2811  assert(isa<SExtInst>(Ext) && "Unexpected ext type!");
2812  LType = ISD::SEXTLOAD;
2813  }
2814 
2815  return isLoadExtLegal(LType, VT, LoadVT);
2816  }
2817 
2818  /// Return true if any actual instruction that defines a value of type FromTy
2819  /// implicitly zero-extends the value to ToTy in the result register.
2820  ///
2821  /// The function should return true when it is likely that the truncate can
2822  /// be freely folded with an instruction defining a value of FromTy. If
2823  /// the defining instruction is unknown (because you're looking at a
2824  /// function argument, PHI, etc.) then the target may require an
2825  /// explicit truncate, which is not necessarily free, but this function
2826  /// does not deal with those cases.
2827  /// Targets must return false when FromTy >= ToTy.
2828  virtual bool isZExtFree(Type *FromTy, Type *ToTy) const {
2829  return false;
2830  }
2831 
2832  virtual bool isZExtFree(EVT FromTy, EVT ToTy) const { return false; }
2833  virtual bool isZExtFree(LLT FromTy, LLT ToTy, const DataLayout &DL,
2834  LLVMContext &Ctx) const {
2835  return isZExtFree(getApproximateEVTForLLT(FromTy, DL, Ctx),
2836  getApproximateEVTForLLT(ToTy, DL, Ctx));
2837  }
2838

2840  /// zero-extension.
2841  virtual bool isSExtCheaperThanZExt(EVT FromTy, EVT ToTy) const {
2842  return false;
2843  }

2845  /// Return true if this constant should be sign extended when promoting to
2846  /// a larger type.
2847  virtual bool signExtendConstant(const ConstantInt *C) const { return false; }

2866  /// Return true if the target supplies and combines to a paired load
2867  /// two loaded values of type LoadedType next to each other in memory.
2868  /// RequiredAlignment gives the minimal alignment constraints that must be met
2869  /// to be able to select this paired load.
2870  ///
2871  /// This information is *not* used to generate actual paired loads, but it is
2872  /// used to generate a sequence of loads that is easier to combine into a
2873  /// paired load.
2874  /// For instance, something like this:
2875  /// a = load i64* addr
2876  /// b = trunc i64 a to i32
2877  /// c = lshr i64 a, 32
2878  /// d = trunc i64 c to i32
2879  /// will be optimized into:
2880  /// b = load i32* addr1
2881  /// d = load i32* addr2
2882  /// Where addr1 = addr2 +/- sizeof(i32).
2883  ///
2884  /// In other words, unless the target performs a post-isel load combining,
2885  /// this information should not be provided because it will generate more
2886  /// loads.
2887  virtual bool hasPairedLoad(EVT /*LoadedType*/,
2888  Align & /*RequiredAlignment*/) const {
2889  return false;
2890  }

3007  /// Returns true if \p MI can be combined with another instruction to
3008  /// form TargetOpcode::G_FMAD. \p N may be an TargetOpcode::G_FADD,
3009  /// TargetOpcode::G_FSUB, or an TargetOpcode::G_FMUL which will be
3010  /// distributed into an fadd/fsub.
3011  virtual bool isFMADLegal(const MachineInstr &MI, LLT Ty) const {
3012  assert((MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::G_FADD ||
3013  MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::G_FSUB ||
3014  MI.getOpcode() == TargetOpcode::G_FMUL) &&
3015  "unexpected node in FMAD forming combine");
3016  switch (Ty.getScalarSizeInBits()) {
3017  case 16:
3018  return isOperationLegal(TargetOpcode::G_FMAD, MVT::f16);
3019  case 32:
3020  return isOperationLegal(TargetOpcode::G_FMAD, MVT::f32);
3021  case 64:
3022  return isOperationLegal(TargetOpcode::G_FMAD, MVT::f64);
3023  default:
3024  break;
3025  }
3026 
3027  return false;
3028  }

3095  /// Try to convert math with an overflow comparison into the corresponding DAG
3096  /// node operation. Targets may want to override this independently of whether
3097  /// the operation is legal/custom for the given type because it may obscure
3098  /// matching of other patterns.
3099  virtual bool shouldFormOverflowOp(unsigned Opcode, EVT VT,
3100  bool MathUsed) const {
3101  // TODO: The default logic is inherited from code in CodeGenPrepare.
3102  // The opcode should not make a difference by default?
3103  if (Opcode != ISD::UADDO)
3104  return false;
3105 
3106  // Allow the transform as long as we have an integer type that is not
3107  // obviously illegal and unsupported and if the math result is used
3108  // besides the overflow check. On some targets (e.g. SPARC), it is
3109  // not profitable to form on overflow op if the math result has no
3110  // concrete users.
3111  if (VT.isVector())
3112  return false;
3113  return MathUsed && (VT.isSimple() || !isOperationExpand(Opcode, VT));
3114  }

3397  void setIndexedModeAction(unsigned IdxMode, MVT VT, unsigned Shift,
3398  LegalizeAction Action) {
3399  assert(VT.isValid() && IdxMode < ISD::LAST_INDEXED_MODE &&
3400  (unsigned)Action < 0xf && "Table isn't big enough!");
3401  unsigned Ty = (unsigned)VT.SimpleTy;
3402  IndexedModeActions[Ty][IdxMode] &= ~(0xf << Shift);
3403  IndexedModeActions[Ty][IdxMode] |= ((uint16_t)Action) << Shift;
3404  }
3405 
3406  LegalizeAction getIndexedModeAction(unsigned IdxMode, MVT VT,
3407  unsigned Shift) const {
3408  assert(IdxMode < ISD::LAST_INDEXED_MODE && VT.isValid() &&
3409  "Table isn't big enough!");
3410  unsigned Ty = (unsigned)VT.SimpleTy;
3411  return (LegalizeAction)((IndexedModeActions[Ty][IdxMode] >> Shift) & 0xf);
3412  }
3413 
3414 protected:
3415  /// Return true if the extension represented by \p I is free.
3416  /// \pre \p I is a sign, zero, or fp extension and
3417  /// is[Z|FP]ExtFree of the related types is not true.
3418  virtual bool isExtFreeImpl(const Instruction *I) const { return false; }
3419 
3420  /// Depth that GatherAllAliases should should continue looking for chain
3421  /// dependencies when trying to find a more preferable chain. As an
3422  /// approximation, this should be more than the number of consecutive stores
3423  /// expected to be merged.
3424  unsigned GatherAllAliasesMaxDepth;
3425 
3426  /// \brief Specify maximum number of store instructions per memset call.
3427  ///
3428  /// When lowering \@llvm.memset this field specifies the maximum number of
3429  /// store operations that may be substituted for the call to memset. Targets
3430  /// must set this value based on the cost threshold for that target. Targets
3431  /// should assume that the memset will be done using as many of the largest
3432  /// store operations first, followed by smaller ones, if necessary, per
3433  /// alignment restrictions. For example, storing 9 bytes on a 32-bit machine
3434  /// with 16-bit alignment would result in four 2-byte stores and one 1-byte
3435  /// store. This only applies to setting a constant array of a constant size.
3436  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemset;
3437  /// Likewise for functions with the OptSize attribute.
3438  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemsetOptSize;
3439 
3440  /// \brief Specify maximum number of store instructions per memcpy call.
3441  ///
3442  /// When lowering \@llvm.memcpy this field specifies the maximum number of
3443  /// store operations that may be substituted for a call to memcpy. Targets
3444  /// must set this value based on the cost threshold for that target. Targets
3445  /// should assume that the memcpy will be done using as many of the largest
3446  /// store operations first, followed by smaller ones, if necessary, per
3447  /// alignment restrictions. For example, storing 7 bytes on a 32-bit machine
3448  /// with 32-bit alignment would result in one 4-byte store, a one 2-byte store
3449  /// and one 1-byte store. This only applies to copying a constant array of
3450  /// constant size.
3451  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemcpy;
3452  /// Likewise for functions with the OptSize attribute.
3453  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemcpyOptSize;
3454  /// \brief Specify max number of store instructions to glue in inlined memcpy.
3455  ///
3456  /// When memcpy is inlined based on MaxStoresPerMemcpy, specify maximum number
3457  /// of store instructions to keep together. This helps in pairing and
3458  // vectorization later on.
3459  unsigned MaxGluedStoresPerMemcpy = 0;
3460 
3461  /// \brief Specify maximum number of load instructions per memcmp call.
3462  ///
3463  /// When lowering \@llvm.memcmp this field specifies the maximum number of
3464  /// pairs of load operations that may be substituted for a call to memcmp.
3465  /// Targets must set this value based on the cost threshold for that target.
3466  /// Targets should assume that the memcmp will be done using as many of the
3467  /// largest load operations first, followed by smaller ones, if necessary, per
3468  /// alignment restrictions. For example, loading 7 bytes on a 32-bit machine
3469  /// with 32-bit alignment would result in one 4-byte load, a one 2-byte load
3470  /// and one 1-byte load. This only applies to copying a constant array of
3471  /// constant size.
3472  unsigned MaxLoadsPerMemcmp;
3473  /// Likewise for functions with the OptSize attribute.
3474  unsigned MaxLoadsPerMemcmpOptSize;
3475 
3476  /// \brief Specify maximum number of store instructions per memmove call.
3477  ///
3478  /// When lowering \@llvm.memmove this field specifies the maximum number of
3479  /// store instructions that may be substituted for a call to memmove. Targets
3480  /// must set this value based on the cost threshold for that target. Targets
3481  /// should assume that the memmove will be done using as many of the largest
3482  /// store operations first, followed by smaller ones, if necessary, per
3483  /// alignment restrictions. For example, moving 9 bytes on a 32-bit machine
3484  /// with 8-bit alignment would result in nine 1-byte stores. This only
3485  /// applies to copying a constant array of constant size.
3486  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemmove;
3487  /// Likewise for functions with the OptSize attribute.
3488  unsigned MaxStoresPerMemmoveOptSize;
3489 
3490  /// Tells the code generator that select is more expensive than a branch if
3491  /// the branch is usually predicted right.
3492  bool PredictableSelectIsExpensive;
3493 
3494  /// \see enableExtLdPromotion.
3495  bool EnableExtLdPromotion;
3496 
3497  /// Return true if the value types that can be represented by the specified
3498  /// register class are all legal.
3499  bool isLegalRC(const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI,
3500  const TargetRegisterClass &RC) const;
3501 
3502  /// Replace/modify any TargetFrameIndex operands with a targte-dependent
3503  /// sequence of memory operands that is recognized by PrologEpilogInserter.
3504  MachineBasicBlock *emitPatchPoint(MachineInstr &MI,
3505  MachineBasicBlock *MBB) const;
3506 
3507  bool IsStrictFPEnabled;
3508 };

3533  // Lets target to control the following reassociation of operands: (op (op x,
3534  // c1), y) -> (op (op x, y), c1) where N0 is (op x, c1) and N1 is y. By
3535  // default consider profitable any case where N0 has single use. This
3536  // behavior reflects the condition replaced by this target hook call in the
3537  // DAGCombiner. Any particular target can implement its own heuristic to
3538  // restrict common combiner.

3713  /// Look at Op. At this point, we know that only the DemandedBits bits of the
3714  /// result of Op are ever used downstream. If we can use this information to
3715  /// simplify Op, create a new simplified DAG node and return true, returning
3716  /// the original and new nodes in Old and New. Otherwise, analyze the
3717  /// expression and return a mask of KnownOne and KnownZero bits for the
3718  /// expression (used to simplify the caller). The KnownZero/One bits may only
3719  /// be accurate for those bits in the Demanded masks.
3720  /// \p AssumeSingleUse When this parameter is true, this function will
3721  /// attempt to simplify \p Op even if there are multiple uses.
3722  /// Callers are responsible for correctly updating the DAG based on the
3723  /// results of this function, because simply replacing replacing TLO.Old
3724  /// with TLO.New will be incorrect when this parameter is true and TLO.Old
3725  /// has multiple uses.
3726  bool SimplifyDemandedBits(SDValue Op, const APInt &DemandedBits,
3727  const APInt &DemandedElts, KnownBits &Known,
3728  TargetLoweringOpt &TLO, unsigned Depth = 0,
3729  bool AssumeSingleUse = false) const;

4000  /// Return true if it is profitable to move this shift by a constant amount
4001  /// through its operand, adjusting any immediate operands as necessary to
4002  /// preserve semantics. This transformation may not be desirable if it
4003  /// disrupts a particularly auspicious target-specific tree (e.g. bitfield
4004  /// extraction in AArch64). By default, it returns true.
4005  ///
4006  /// @param N the shift node
4007  /// @param Level the current DAGCombine legalization level.
4008  virtual bool isDesirableToCommuteWithShift(const SDNode *N,
4009  CombineLevel Level) const {
4010  return true;
4011  }
4012 
4013  // Return AndOrSETCCFoldKind::{AddAnd, ABS} if its desirable to try and
4014  // optimize LogicOp(SETCC0, SETCC1). An example (what is implemented as of
4015  // writing this) is:
4016  // With C as a power of 2 and C != 0 and C != INT_MIN:
4017  // AddAnd:
4018  // (icmp eq A, C) | (icmp eq A, -C)
4019  // -> (icmp eq and(add(A, C), ~(C + C)), 0)
4020  // (icmp ne A, C) & (icmp ne A, -C)w
4021  // -> (icmp ne and(add(A, C), ~(C + C)), 0)
4022  // ABS:
4023  // (icmp eq A, C) | (icmp eq A, -C)
4024  // -> (icmp eq Abs(A), C)
4025  // (icmp ne A, C) & (icmp ne A, -C)w
4026  // -> (icmp ne Abs(A), C)
4027  //
4028  // @param LogicOp the logic op
4029  // @param SETCC0 the first of the SETCC nodes
4030  // @param SETCC0 the second of the SETCC nodes
4031  virtual AndOrSETCCFoldKind isDesirableToCombineLogicOpOfSETCC(
4032  const SDNode *LogicOp, const SDNode *SETCC0, const SDNode *SETCC1) const {
4033  return AndOrSETCCFoldKind::None;
4034  }
4035 
4036  /// Return true if it is profitable to combine an XOR of a logical shift

4039  /// BIC on ARM/AArch64). By default, it returns true.
